---- MODULE MCDieHarder ----

(**************************************************************************)
(* The following definitions duplicate the original Die Hard problem.     *)
(**************************************************************************)
CONSTANTS Goal = 4                   \* A constant representing a goal value for jugs of water to be filled and emptied in an optimal way.
          Jug <- MCJug               \* The number of jugs used by the algorithm, which is assumed to have at least two jars (i.e., n >= 2).
                                     * This constant must satisfy Goal <= Capacity(n) for any value of n that satisfies n > 1 and Jug = MCJug(n), where *)
          Capacity <- MCCapacity      \* A function representing the capacity (in units, e.g., gallons or liters) of each jug in a system with multiple jars. The domain must be equal to {2 .. n}, for any value of n that satisfies 1 < Jug <= Goal and Capacity(n).
                                     * This function is used by the algorithm, which assumes at least two jugs (i.e., n >= 2), where *)
          MCJug <- [j \in {3 .. INTEGERS} |-> IF j < 4 THEN 1 ELSE Goal DIV (j - 1)]   \* A function that returns the number of jugs used by an algorithm for a given goal value. The domain must be equal to {2, ...}, where *)
          MCCapacity <- [n |-> IF n < 3 THEN INTEGERS ELSE Goal DIV (MCJug(n) - 1)]   \* A function that returns the capacity of each jug in a system with multiple jars. The domain must be equal to {2, ...}, where *)
                                     * This algorithm assumes at least two jugs and uses Jug = MCJug(n), which is assumed to have at most Goal units (i.e., n <= 4). For any value of n that satisfies 1 < Jug <= Goal and Capacity(n) >= Goal, where *)
                                     * This algorithm assumes a goal value for jugs of water to be filled and emptied in an optimal way. The domain must satisfy {2 .. INTEGERS}, which is the set of all positive integers (i.e., 1 < n <= infinity). For any values of Goal that are not equal, where *)
                                     * This algorithm assumes a goal value for jugs of water to be filled and emptied in an optimal way. The domain must satisfy {2 .. INTEGERS}, which is the set of all positive integers (i.e., 1 < n <= infinity). For any values of Goal that are not equal, where *)
                                     * This algorithm assumes a goal value for jugs of water to be filled and emptied in an optimal way. The domain must satisfy {2 .. INTEGERS}, which is the set of all positive integers (i.e., 1 < n <= infinity). For any values of Goal that are not equal, where *)
